t Unsettled Balance shows that arguments about rights, obligations, norms, and values have played a profound role in Canadian foreign policy and international relations since the 1990s. The contributors to this volume examine a range of topics – from funding for climate change adaptation to the militarization of humanitarian aid – to collectively explore three key questions. What is the meaning of “ethics” and “security,” and how are they linked? To what extent have considerations of ethics and security changed in the twenty-first century? And what are the implications of a shifting historical context for Canada’s international relations? Their conclusions are essential reading for anyone who wants to understand not only how Canada responds to global challenges but also why it responds the way it does.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relations. 0aNational securityxMoral and ethical aspectszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aAkuffo, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdgar, Alistair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Barbara J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendershot, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHessen, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKitchen, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, W. Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRochlin, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoett, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1